Three hobbies in life: Baseball. Singing. Cooking 🤎

When I’m in the kitchen, everything else in life gets quiet. Cooking reminds me of the happiest, simplest times in life.

Growing up my entire family would sit in the kitchen all evening watching my aunts, mom and grandma whip up the most delicious meals. Always made from scratch & making the best memories ❤️ 

So in summary: they might disown me if I didn’t know how to make things from scratch too 😜

Jean, this one’s for you 💚

Tonight we won an Emmy for our show honoring @raysbaseball late bullpen catcher Jean Ramirez who died by suicide last year.

FaceTimed Jean’s mom (8 second mark of the video), Toni after we won 💚

This Emmy is for Jean, his parents Toni & Carlos who opened their hearts to the world to advocate for mental health & anyone struggling. 

When we asked to do this show, I didn’t expect two grieving parents to be willing to open their hearts & share their words with such willingness and eloquence. But they did. They did it to honor their son & to spread a message that it’s okay to not be okay. Love you both dearly.

Thank you to the Rays players, who when we asked if they’d speak about Jean & his memory, didn’t hesitate. It’s not an easy topic but @sweet_n_lowe5 @rthomp26, Mike Zunino and Kyle Snyder opened their hearts & souls to the world about their friend Jean.

To Jean: you are so missed. We love you 💚

🥹💕 Today was the final day of class this semester teaching my students at @iumediaschool and I could not be more proud of their work 👏🏻❤️

People always think I’ve gone crazy when I say I go back to cold Indiana during the baseball offseason to teach instead of staying in the sunshine 😬 These amazing students are why. What the @iumediaschool is doing is incredible ❤️

During the semester, they anchored in studio highlights, conducted interviews, edited together the best sports stories & heard from some amazing guest speakers. 

The learning goes both ways. I’ve learned things from my students every single semester over the last 7 years of teaching & I’m so grateful for their hard work & insight. 

Huge thank you to our phenomenal guest speakers this semester for sacrificing their time to impart their wisdom on my students. @realroflo @laurenshehadi @mmarakovits @cayleighgriffin @melanielynnen. You are all amazing and we appreciated you so much ❤️

🫶🏼 A compilation of some of my favorite women in sports on National Women in Sports day.

I know there are some who feel days like this aren’t necessary, as it has become pretty common for women to be in sports, but please know that we don’t see this as a day to divide anyone.

We see it as a day to celebrate how far we’ve come, and to acknowledge those who supported us on our journey, which includes so many men in the industry. 

I’ve been supported by some amazing men throughout my career, and the women have been my backbone.

There’s room for everyone in sports and I’m grateful to work with a qualified group of both men and women on a daily basis ♥️

The first picture is my favorite because here’s a young girl named Connelly, who has been raised to know nothing but women in sports and sees her dreams as fully achievable. That melted my heart 🫠 That’s what we want ♥️

#nationalwomeninsportsday

👊🏼These are the stories you can get behind.

Early in Jeffrey Springs career he worked at the YMCA & in landscaping to make ends meet while chasing his ⚾️ dream.

He wasn’t a high draft pick. He was DFA’ed twice. He started in the bullpen. Tore his ACL. Recovered & came back as a starter.

Now? He has a $31 million contract.

And today, @jsprings19 had this to say to the other “not supposed to make it” guys.

“Statistically I wasnt supposed to make it. I hope someone hears my story & says, ‘He did it, I can too.”’

💙 Most of the time, we post about a player’s home runs — their happy moments on the field. But it’s important to post about the uncomfortable, or challenging topics too.

Infertility struggles is one of those topics, and it’s something more people struggle with than we could possibly know.

But there’s hope. 

And after having their first child, Brandon Lowe & his wife Madison want other couples to have the option to have kids without worrying about the major financial burden of IVF. 

The Lowe’s have been open about their own journey to becoming parents and it was pretty inspiring to hear @sweet_n_lowe5 open up about this on the broadcast. They support @babyquestgrants, an incredible foundation that helps provide financial support to couples going through infertility procedures. 

When a player uses their platform like this, it’s powerful. 💙

It’s time 🔴⚪️

🥹 Growing up in Indiana, I’d come to Wrigley with my dad once a summer. This is where my love for baseball started. 

We weren’t exactly rich 😂, so we always got seats in the way back. 

This is a full circle moment for me. If you would’ve told me and my dad 15 years ago when I was younger that he’d be watching me do sideline for a national Cubs game on Apple TV, we both might’ve passed out.

So dad, this games for you 💙 Thanks for taking me to all those games growing up. Even when we got stuck sitting behind one of those damn poles at Wrigley.

“At that point, I wasn’t scared of anything. Those sharks were just regular fish to me. I’d do anything for my family.”

Tonight, we hear Yandy Diaz’s story. 

While trying to defect from Cuba, he was arrested 4 times, spending 4 months in jail. 

He sat on a raft, eyeing down sharks — focused on his final destination— and a better life for his family.

Now? He’s an All Star, one of the best hitters in the league & what this clubhouse calls their “spark plug.”

💙 “I know what that’s like. My grandma passed of cancer.”

If you watch nothing else today, watch Elijah’s reaction to meeting his favorite player, Yandy Diaz. Speechless joy 🥹

Elijah is 10 and has bone cancer. But it went much deeper for Yandy than just a meet & greet. 

He knows what Elijah is going through.

Yandy defected from Cuba to find a better life to support his grandmother, who was dying of cancer in Cuba.

He sat on a raft for 12 hours after trying to defect 4 prior times & being arrested 4 times, just to help someone he loved most in their fight with cancer.

So Elijah, and his story/bravery? It truly touched Diaz & all of us at the game today.

Dementia can go straight to the pits of hell.

It kills me that I didn’t make it in time to say goodbye. I was hours away from seeing you.

Rest in sweet peace. I will love you forever Grandma.

This was the last time I saw you. You remembered me but not my name.

Please consider donating to fund research to fight this bullshit disease that must have come from the devil himself.

If you make a donation, please make it in my grandma, Joe Ann’s, name. The link is in my bio.

It’s a horrific, life sucking disease. 

It leaves you feeling helpless, guilty for not being more patient with them, and constantly longing to see glimpses of the person you once loved. 

Watching my dad take care of his mom throughout the last years of her life showed me something I had forgotten: love is a commitment. Love is a choice. 

On days, Dad, where you couldn’t even see shadows of the person who was once your mom, you took care of her.

On days where she was harsh with her words, because she had no idea what she was saying and meant none if it, you never left her.

On days where she refused to get out of bed, you knelt by her and fed her.

On days she couldn’t physically get up, you picked her up.

When no one else was there for her, you were.

Even on days where your patience was tested with her, you never left her. 

It wasn’t pretty. But love isn’t pretty.

You are the best son she could have ever asked for. You’re the best dad I could ever ask for and no one can ever measure up to that type of love. 

If your family is going through this, keep fighting, keep loving and keep showing up. I wish I had shown up more.

And know that their heart remembers what their mind forgot. 💙 

Grandma, I hope I make you proud. She’s where I got my stubbornness from, which is both a flaw and a strength, but damn I’m grateful for the strength it has at times provided.

🏆 We won an Emmy tonight for our Rays All Access feature show on the late, great Don Zimmer. 

Zim spent 66 years in professional baseball. He was a former Rays coach, former Cubs Manager, former Yankees bench coach — he impacted so many teams. And his wife Soot? By his side through all of it. 

She’s 92 years old and sharp as a tack. 

She sat down with us for a 1-on-1 interview remembering her dear husband and I loved this story that she told about how they met. She asked him out first, and he said no 😂

Thank you to the entire Zimmer family for taking the time to interview with us, thank you @evan.longoria3 for your words on Don Zimmer’s legacy in this show & thank you to our wonderful @ballysportsflorida crew. My producer, editor and cameramen worked so hard on this show and they made it what it is ♥️ Hope we made Don proud.

Tyler Glasnow is one of the first players I covered and met when I started with the Rays in 2019.

For my last five seasons, he’s been the best interview & best person to cover. Treats everyone as an equal & that is immensely appreciated.

We may argue on camera about the proper way to cut asparagus & I’m sure doing interviews with me multiple times on a weekly basis was never the highlight of his week, but it was one of the highlights of my baseball career. 

His family was also a highlight.

His parents became a couple of my closest Rays friends throughout those five years. Covering a player with a good heart, filthy stuff, and an incredible family is truly the trifecta. 

It’s been a pleasure and he will be sorely missed in that clubhouse. Thank you for memories @glasnowt .
